Step 11: Enable and Configure SSH Server
SSH allows you to connect to Kali remotely from other machines — useful for running commands and transferring files during lab exercises.

SSH Server Configuration

bash
# Check SSH service status:
sudo systemctl status ssh

# Enable SSH to start automatically on boot:
sudo systemctl enable ssh

# Start SSH now:
sudo systemctl start ssh

# Verify SSH is running and listening on port 22:
ss -tlnp | grep :22
# Should show: LISTEN  0  128  0.0.0.0:22

# Find Kali's IP for SSH connections from other machines:
hostname -I

# Test SSH from another machine (e.g Windows PowerShell):
ssh username@<kali-IP>

# Generate SSH key pair (run on the machine you connect FROM):
ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -C 'lab-key'

# Copy public key to Kali for passwordless login:
ssh-copy-id username@<kali-IP>
SSH Security Hardening for Lab

Disable root login: Edit /etc/ssh/sshd_config → set PermitRootLogin no
Change default port (optional): Set Port 2222 instead of 22 — reduces automated scanning noise
Use SSH keys: Disable password authentication after setting up key auth — set PasswordAuthentication no
Restart SSH after changes: sudo systemctl restart ssh
