Step 15: Take a Snapshot — Lab Baseline
Before starting any lab exercises, take a VM snapshot. This allows you to restore Kali to a clean state at any time — essential for a lab environment.

Snapshot Management

bash
# In VMware — take snapshot from the menu:
# VM → Snapshot → Take Snapshot
# Name: 'Kali-Clean-Baseline'
# Description: 'Post-install, fully updated, all tools verified'

# In VirtualBox — take snapshot:
# Machine → Take Snapshot
# Name: 'Kali-Clean-Baseline'

# From command line (VMware):
# vmrun snapshot /path/to/kali.vmx 'Kali-Clean-Baseline'

# When to take snapshots:
# - After fresh installation and configuration  ← do this now
# - Before testing any new exploit or technique
# - After completing each lab successfully

# Restoring a snapshot:
# VMware: VM → Snapshot → Snapshot Manager → select → Restore
# VirtualBox: Machine → Restore Snapshot
Why Snapshots Are Essential in a Security Lab

Mistakes happen: Misconfigurations, bad payloads, or accidental file deletion can break your attack machine. Snapshots let you recover in seconds.
Clean state for each exercise: Some exercises modify system state — snapshots let you start fresh for each test.
Compare before/after: Snapshots let you see exactly what changed during an attack — valuable for learning.
Multiple configurations: Maintain snapshots for different lab configurations — one with BloodHound running, one clean, one with specific tools configured.
